    <h3>Blockifying</h3>  
    <p> Blockifying is apparently the technical term for separating elements on a page into compartments. Any page of content can be split up into smaller blocks and sub-blocks. Each of these blocks can be placed into a container like <b>div</b>. This skill can be practiced by either drawing boxes around each element or even by printing the page and cutting the blocks out. Even shapes like circles are really just blocks.
    </p>
    <h3>HTML Structure</h3>
    <p>Aside from blockifying, you can also think of an HTML document as having a tree like structure. You can see this structure by following the indentations along the left end of the HTML code. For example, many trees will start with a <b>body</b> and the next line will have an indented element. This element is the next branch of the tree. Multiple <b>div</b> sections can be either along the same branch or they can be two separate limbs of the tree. 
